<p>We say things like ‚Äúthe sun is hot because of the energy released by the fusion of hydrogen atoms‚Äù. We could construct a graph of concepts and relations, linking <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">the sun</code> to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">hot</code> via some <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">is</code> relation, and ‚Ä¶</p>

<p>But <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">the sun</code>, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">hydrogen atoms</code>, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">energy</code>, ‚Ä¶ are not basis concepts (and neither are <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">because</code>, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">released</code>, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">fusion</code>, ‚Ä¶ basis relations), they are extremely complicated ideas built up by experience and reasoning.</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">the sun</code> could be represented as a graph of ‚Äòmore basic‚Äô concepts, ‚Äúthe bright thing that moves across the sky‚Äù. And again, these concepts and relations could be decomposed.</p>

